data.enText: walk/climb
to move quickly, especially with difficulty, using your hands to help you
She managed to scramble over the wall.

data.chText: 我们进来时，他慌忙站起身。
data.enText: He scrambled to his feet as we came in.
push/fight
to push, fight or compete with others in order to get or to reach sth
The audience scrambled for the exits.

data.chText: 顾客争先恐后地抢购最便宜的特价商品。
data.enText: Shoppers were scrambling to get the best bargains.
achieve sth with difficulty
to manage to achieve sth with difficulty, or in a hurry, without much control

data.chText: 科克队苦战莫纳亨队，以1:0获胜。
data.enText: Cork scrambled a 1–0 win over Monaghan.

data.chText: 欧文勉力把球捅入网窝。
data.enText: Owen managed to scramble the ball into the net.
eggs
to cook an egg by mixing the white and yellow parts together and heating them, sometimes with milk and butter
scrambled eggs
telephone/radio

data.chText: 扰码，倒频（改变电话或无线电信号，听众只有通过专门设备才能收听）
data.enText: to change the way that a telephone or radio message sounds so that only people with special equipment can understand it
scrambled satellite signals
confuse thoughts
to confuse sb's thoughts, ideas, etc. so that they have no order

data.chText: 酒精似乎扰乱了他的脑子。
data.enText: Alcohol seemed to have scrambled his brain.
aircraft

data.chText: 命令（飞机）紧急起飞；紧急起飞
data.enText: to order that planes, etc. should take off immediately in an emergency; to take off immediately in an emergency

data.chText: 直升机接到命令，紧急起飞前去营救三个登山的年轻人。
data.enText: A helicopter was scrambled to help rescue three young climbers.

data.chText: 命令刚一下达，他们便紧急起飞。
data.enText: They scrambled as soon as the call came through.
difficult walk/climb

data.chText: （尤指需要手脚并用的）艰难行走，爬，攀登
data.enText: a difficult walk or climb over rough ground, especially one in which you have to use your hands
push/fight
a situation in which people push, fight or compete with each other in order to get or do sth

data.chText: 人们不顾一切地抢占最好的座位。
data.enText: There was a mad scramble for the best seats.
motorcycle race
a race for motorcycles over rough ground

means: (尤指需要手脚并用的)艰难行走，爬，攀登

tr: rushing about hastily in an undignified way

example: scramble the message so that nobody can understand it

tr: climb awkwardly, as if by scrambling

value.def: If you scramble over rocks or up a hill, you move quickly over them or up it using your hands to help you.

example.ex: Tourists were scrambling over the rocks looking for the perfect camera angle...
example.tran: 游客们在正爬上岩石寻找最佳的拍摄角度。

example.ex: He scrambled up a steep bank.
example.tran: 他攀上了一个陡峭的河堤。

value.def: If you scramble to a different place or position, you move there in a hurried, awkward way.

example.ex: Ann threw back the covers and scrambled out of bed...
example.tran: 安掀开被子，急忙下了床。

value.def: If a number of people scramble for something, they compete energetically with each other for it.

example.ex: More than three million fans are expected to scramble for tickets...
example.tran: 预计会有超过 300 万的球迷抢购门票。

example.ex: Business is booming and foreigners are scrambling to invest.
example.tran: 商业繁荣，外国人争相投资。

example.ex: ...a scramble to get a seat on the early morning flight.

gramarinfo.label: usu sing, oft N <l>for</l> n, N to-inf

value.def: If you scramble eggs, you break them, mix them together and then heat and stir the mixture in a pan.

example.ex: Make the toast and scramble the eggs.
example.tran: 把面包烤一下并炒些鸡蛋。

value.def: If a device scrambles a radio or telephone message, it interferes with the sound so that the message can only be understood by someone with special equipment.

example.ex: The latest machines scramble the messages so that the conversation cannot easily be intercepted.
example.tran: 最新的机器对信号作扰频处理，通话就不易被侦听了。

value.tran: 倒换(无线电或电话信号)的频率(使只有持特殊仪器的人才能接收)
